subject: Add mechanism to limit Request ID size

values.-1: This patch needs further work before it can be merged
values.+1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

Shouldn't this be a standard size request-id length across openstack projects?

Patch Set 1:

as mentioned in the commit message initial set to 0 so this is backwards compatible with our current behavior.

The https://review.openstack.org/#/c/210026/ sets it something sensible and we can debate what that sensible value should be.

Patch Set 1:

I think this looks good, but I have a question.  Suppose a glance admin sets this at 64 and some other openstack project notices this same problem, implements a similar fix, but their admin sets it to 68.  Someone makes a request to that other service with a 68-char request ID, and that service contacts glance for some reason.  At that point, your code will throw an exception ending the request.  I'm just wondering whether it would be better to just strip the request-id header in this case instead of throwing an exception.

Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Abhishek please ping me when you have a +1 on this and will remove -W

Patch Set 1:

For such interop cases we need a standard size. Good topic for CPL meeting.

Patch Set 1:

Brian,

I see your point but I don't really agree. Our basic behavior is to fail early what ever we do and we don't truncate other oversized data either. IMHO if there is other OpenStack projects that accepts Request IDs sent to the service and/or forwards it to Glance, the admins needs to correlate their limits between services.

Would be horrible if for example swift would just truncate the objects sent because glance admin set larger large_object_size that swift admin.

Patch Set 1:

Erno,

I think you're right.  I guess what I was really getting at is that the length needs to be coordinated among the various projects.
